{"title_page": "Verb of fearing", "text_new": "In [[Latin grammar]], a '''verb of fearing''' is one that pertains to [[fear]] or concern (often ''timeo'', ''terreor'', ''metuo'', and ''vereor''). This set of verbs is grammatically notable because it inverts the sense of a following [[Final clause|purposive clause]], at least relative to the intuition of speakers of many non-Latin languages.\n\nVerbs of fearing can be used three different ways: fear of a person or thing, fear of performing an action and fear of an event occurring.\n* Fear of a '''person''' or '''thing''' is expressed using a verb of fearing (e.g. timeo) and a noun, either in the dative or the accusative. Mountford notes that there is no general rule on which case should be used, although different meanings can be conveyed depending on use.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mountford |first1=Sir James |title=Bradley's Arnold Latin Prose Composition |publisher=Bristol Classical Press |isbn=0-86292-150-3 |page=141}}</ref>\n** ''Hostes timet'' - 'he fears the enemy'.\n** ''filio timet pater'' - 'the father fears for his son'.\n** ''furem pomis timet agricola'' - 'the farmer fears the thief for his apples'.\n* Fear of '''performing an action''' is expressed using an infinitive, much like in English.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Morwood |first1=James |title=A Latin Grammar |date=1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-860199-9 |page=102}}</ref>\n** ''timeo hoc facere'' . - 'I am afraid to do this'.\n* Fear of '''an event occurring''' is expressed using the conjunctions 'ne', conveying that, with regards to the event occurring, the negative is wished and the positive feared, and 'ut', conveying that the positive is wished and the negative feared.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gildersleeve |first1=B.L. |last2=Lodge |first2=Gonzalez |title=Latin Grammar |date=1867 |publisher=Bristol Classical Press |isbn=1-85399-521-5 |pages=349\u2013351}}</ref> These conjunctions are then followed by the subjunctive, according to the sequence of tenses, with primary sequence tenses generally being followed by the present or perfect subjunctives and historic (or secondary) sequence tenses being followed by the imperfect or pluperfect subjunctives.\n** ''vereor ne hostis veniat'' - 'I fear lest the enemy come', 'I fear that the enemy is coming'.\n** ''vereor ne dum minuere velim laborem augeam'', Cicero De Legibus I.4.12 - 'I fear that, while I wish to lessen the toil, I am increasing it'.\n** ''timeo ne tibi nihil praeter lacrimas queam reddere'', Cicero Pro Plancio 42.101 - 'I am afraid that I can give nothing in return save tears'.\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book |last1=Mountford |first1=Sir James |title=Bradley's Arnold Latin Prose Composition |publisher=Bristol Classical Press |isbn=0-86292-150-3}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Morwood |first1=James |title=A Latin Grammar |date=1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-860199-9}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Gildersleeve |first1=B.L. |last2=Lodge |first2=Gonzalez |title=Latin Grammar |date=1867 |publisher=Bristol Classical Press |isbn=1-85399-521-5}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Kennedy |first1=Benjamin Hall |last2=Mountford |first2=Sir James |title=The Revised Latin Primer |date=1962 |publisher=Longman |isbn=978-0-582-36240-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/revisedlatinprim00kenn }}\n*{{cite web |last1=Ayer |first1=Meagan |title=Allen and Greenough's Latin Grammar: Substantive Clauses of Purpose |url=http://dcc.dickinson.edu/grammar/latin/substantive-clauses-purpose |website=Dickinson College Commentaries |accessdate=23 May 2019}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Latin language]]\n[[Category:Verb types]]\n", "text_old": "In [[Latin grammar]], a '''verb of fearing''' is one that pertains to [[fear]] or concern (often ''timeo'', ''terreor'', ''metuo'', and ''vereor''). This set of verbs is grammatically notable because it inverts the sense of a following [[Final clause|purposive clause]], at least relative to the intuition of speakers of many non-Latin languages.\n\nVerbs of fearing can be used three different ways: fear of a person or thing, fear of performing an action and fear of an event occurring.\n* Fear of a '''person''' or '''thing''' is expressed using a verb of fearing (e.g. timeo) and a noun, either in the dative or the accusative. Mountford notes that there is no general rule on which case should be used, although different meanings can be conveyed depending on use.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mountford |first1=Sir James |title=Bradley's Arnold Latin Prose Composition |publisher=Bristol Classical Press |isbn=0-86292-150-3 |page=141}}</ref>\n** ''Hostes timet'' - 'he fears the enemy'.\n** ''filio timet pater'' - 'the father fears for his son'.\n** ''furem pomis timet agricola'' - 'the farmer fears the thief for his apples'.\n* Fear of '''performing an action''' is expressed using an infinite, much like in English.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Morwood |first1=James |title=A Latin Grammar |date=1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-860199-9 |page=102}}</ref>\n** ''timeo hoc facere'' . - 'I am afraid to do this'.\n* Fear of '''an event occurring''' is expressed using the conjunctions 'ne', conveying that, with regards to the event occurring, the negative is wished and the positive feared, and 'ut', conveying that the positive is wished and the negative feared.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gildersleeve |first1=B.L. |last2=Lodge |first2=Gonzalez |title=Latin Grammar |date=1867 |publisher=Bristol Classical Press |isbn=1-85399-521-5 |pages=349\u2013351}}</ref> These conjunctions are then followed by the subjunctive, according to the sequence of tenses, with primary sequence tenses generally being followed by the present or perfect subjunctives and historic (or secondary) sequence tenses being followed by the imperfect or pluperfect subjunctives.\n** ''vereor ne hostis veniat'' - 'I fear lest the enemy come', 'I fear that the enemy is coming'.\n** ''vereor ne dum minuere velim laborem augeam'', Cicero De Legibus I.4.12 - 'I fear that, while I wish to lessen the toil, I am increasing it'.\n** ''timeo ne tibi nihil praeter lacrimas queam reddere'', Cicero Pro Plancio 42.101 - 'I am afraid that I can give nothing in return save tears'.\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book |last1=Mountford |first1=Sir James |title=Bradley's Arnold Latin Prose Composition |publisher=Bristol Classical Press |isbn=0-86292-150-3}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Morwood |first1=James |title=A Latin Grammar |date=1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-860199-9}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Gildersleeve |first1=B.L. |last2=Lodge |first2=Gonzalez |title=Latin Grammar |date=1867 |publisher=Bristol Classical Press |isbn=1-85399-521-5}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Kennedy |first1=Benjamin Hall |last2=Mountford |first2=Sir James |title=The Revised Latin Primer |date=1962 |publisher=Longman |isbn=978-0-582-36240-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/revisedlatinprim00kenn }}\n*{{cite web |last1=Ayer |first1=Meagan |title=Allen and Greenough's Latin Grammar: Substantive Clauses of Purpose |url=http://dcc.dickinson.edu/grammar/latin/substantive-clauses-purpose |website=Dickinson College Commentaries |accessdate=23 May 2019}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Latin language]]\n[[Category:Verb types]]\n", "name_user": "PeelitePowellite", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verb_of_fearing"}
